<h1>Proceedings of Commissioners to Settle the Pennsylvania-Virginia Boundary</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<p><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Baltimore, 2731 Aug. 1779</span>. After presenting their respective powers, the commissioners for Virginia (Rev. James Madison and Rev. Robert Andrews; the third commissioner, Thomas Lewis, was absent) exchanged on the following days with the commissioners for Pennsylvania (George Bryan, Rev. John Ewing, and David Rittenhouse) a series of letters proposing and rejecting various lines as the southern boundary of the state of Pennsylvania beyond Maryland. The agreement at length reached on 31 Aug. and signed by the five commissioners proposed To extend Masons and Dixons line due west five degrees of longitude, to be computed from the river Delaware, for the southern boundary of Pennsylvania, and that a meridian drawn from the western extremity thereof to the northern limit of the said state be the western boundary of Pennsylvania forever.</p>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="TSJN-01-03-0087-sn">
<p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ transcript ]">Tr</abbr> (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Library of Congress ]">DLC</span>); 8 p.; printed in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William W. Hening, &lt;i&gt;The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia&lt;/i&gt; ]">Hening,</span> <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">x</span>, 52133. (The agreement as signed by all the commissioners, quoted above, is not in <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ transcript ]">Tr</abbr>, but follows the text of the Proceedings in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William W. Hening, &lt;i&gt;The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia&lt;/i&gt; ]">Hening,</span> <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">x</span>, 533.)</p>
  <p>For the background of the Pennsylvania-Virginia boundary controversy, see several documents printed above, especially <a href="default.xqy?keys=TSJN-print-01-01-02-0117" class="document">Virginia and Pennsylvania Delegates to Inhabitants West of Laurel Hill, 25 July 1775</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=TSJN-print-01-01-02-0236" class="document">TJs Memoranda on the Virginia, Pennsylvania, and Maryland Boundaries, printed under 5 Nov. 1776</a>, with references there. On 18 Dec. 1776 the Virginia Assembly proposed a line yielding the Forks of the Ohio, and <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="TSJN-01-03-02-pb-0078">[78<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=TSJN/Pages/TSJN-01-03/TSJN-01-03-02-pb-0078.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span> for more than two years there was desultory correspondence between the two states on the subject. In Dec. 1778 Virginia proposed that a mixed commission meet to settle the question. Pennsylvania agreed and nominated commissioners on its part. On 24 June 1779 Thomas Lewis, James Madison, and Robert Andrews were appointed commissioners by the Virginia Assembly. See <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Penna. Archives</span>, 1st ser., <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">v-vii</span>, indexes under Virginia; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Journal of the House of Delegates of the Commonwealth of Virginia&lt;/i&gt; (cited by session and date of publication) ]">JHD</span>, Oct. 1777, p. 116; same, Oct. 1778, p. 11112; same, May 1779, p. 1516, 35, 64 (all references are to the 1827 reprints); Paullin and Wright, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Atlas</span>, p. 778, and pl. 97G. For further developments on the boundary dispute during TJs governorship, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=TSJN-print-01-03-02-0222" class="document">Joseph Reed to TJ, 25 Nov.</a>; <a href="default.xqy?keys=TSJN-print-01-03-02-0279" class="document">Huntington to TJ, 30 Dec. 1779</a>; and <a href="default.xqy?keys=TSJN-print-01-03-02-0326" class="document">TJ to Huntington, 9 Feb. 1780</a>.</p></div>
</div>
